        "timing-system",
        "workspace"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "s5",
      "description": "Analyze the within-subject mean time difference and stop when either 20 participants are completed or the 95% Bayesian credible interval excludes zero with a minimum effect size of 5 minutes.",
      "dependencies": [
        "s4"
      ],
      "resources": [
        "analysis"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```
secondary_structured_tool_input:
```json
{
  "response_text": "Hypothesis: Developers who use rubber duck debugging find bugs faster than those who do not. Metric: Time-to-resolution (minutes from bug report to verified fix) per session. Design: Within-subjects crossover: each developer completes 10 debugging tasks with duck and 10 without, randomized order, matched tasks by complexity tier. Confounders: Developer experience, task familiarity, fatigue, task difficulty, presence of colleagues. Stopping rule: Stop after 20 participants or when Bayesian credible interval on mean time difference excludes zero at 95% with minimum effect size of 5 minutes; whichever comes first.",
  "claims": [
    "The experiment is falsifiable.",
    "The metric is time-to-resolution per session.",
    "The design is a within-subjects crossover.",
    "Confounders include experience, familiarity, fatigue, difficulty, and colleague presence.",
    "Stopping occurs after 20 participants or a 95% Bayesian credible interval excluding zero with a 5-minute minimum effect size."
  ],
  "evidence": [
    "Matched task complexity tiers.",
    "Randomized order.",
    "Isolated sessions.",
    "Explicit stopping rule."
  ]
}
```
